Directed by Kathryn Bigelow. With Jeremy Renner, Anthony Mackie, Brian Geraghty.

Plot: Iraq. Forced to play a dangerous game of cat-and-mouse in the chaos of war, an elite Army bomb squad unit must come together in a city where everyone is a potential enemy and every object could be a deadly bomb.

Jeremy Renner won the &quot;Breakthrough Actor Award&quot; and Kathryn Bigelow took home the &quot;Director Award&quot; at the 2009 Hollywood Film Festival

The Hurt Locker won two IFP Gotham Awards, for best feature and best ensemble performance.

The Palm Springs Film Festival will honor Jeremy Renner with its &quot;Breakthrough Actor&quot; award.

The National Board of Review (NBR) chose The Hurt Locker as one of the top 10 films of 2009, and awarded Jeremy Renner its &quot;breakthrough actor&quot; award.

The Hurt Locker won the Washington DC Area Film Critics Awards (WAFCA) award for Best Director, making Kathryn Bigelow the first woman to ever receive the honor. The film also won the award for &quot;Best Ensemble Cast.&quot;

Time Magazine has chosen The Hurt Locker as one of the top 10 films of 2009.

The Associated Press (AP) Critics have selected The Hurt Locker as one of the top ten films of the decade.

The Associated Press Critics have also selected The Hurt Locker' as the best film in their &quot;Top Ten of 2009&quot;. Said the film writers, The Hurt Locker is the &quot;first great Iraq war film (which) proves so universal that it can stand among the classics from past wars. Director Kathryn Bigelow drops viewers in at ground zero for a disturbingly close and claustrophobic look at the stresses and strains of disabling bombs for a living. Ably supported by Anthony Mackie and Brian Geraghty, Jeremy Renner is fierce, frightening and fearless as a sergeant so addicted to the adrenaline rush of defusing explosives that he can no longer conceive of another way of life.&quot;

The Alliance of Women Film Journalists has awarded The Hurt Locker with six awards including &quot;Best Film&quot;, &quot;Best Director&quot;, &quot;Best Woman Director&quot;, and &quot;Best Ensemble Cast&quot;. Kathryn Bigelow also received its &quot;Woman's Image&quot; award and &quot;This Year's Outstanding Achievement By a Woman In The Film Industry&quot; award.

The Los Angeles Film Critics Association (LAFCA) has selected The Hurt Locker as the best picture of 2009. The LAFCA also chose Kathryn Bigelow as &quot;Best director&quot;.

The American Film Institute (AFI) has selected The Hurt Locker as the top drama of the year and is one of its ten selected &quot;Best films of 2009.&quot;

The Hurt Locker swept up five wins at The Boston Society of Film Critics awards including &quot;Best Picture&quot;. The film also took the honors for &quot;Best Director&quot; (Kathryn Bigelow), &quot;Best Actor&quot; (Jeremy Renner), &quot;Best Cinematography&quot; (Barry Ackroyd), and &quot;Best Film Editing&quot; (Chris Innis and Bob Murawski). It was the first time in the organization's 30-year history that one film took home five awards.

